result.execSummary:
The defendant Trisha Lynne Knutson was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Possession of Narcotic Drugs, a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(3g)(am).
  • Bail Jumping-Felony, a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 946.49(1)(b).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Hearing on petition of return of property proceeded.  Court is in receipt of the letter dated December 4, 2014, from Assistant City Attorney Behling which states there is not objection to return of the property/money. Court grants petition.  Filed, signed Order.

Defendant Trisha Lynne Knutson in court with attorney Laurence M Moon.  Defendant Trisha Lynne Knutson in custody.  Patricia I. Daugherty appeared for the State of Wisconsin.
AS TO COUNT 4:
The Court sentenced the defendant to a MAXIMUM TERM OF IMPRISONMENT of 24 MONTHS, concurrent to COUNT 5 and consecutive to any other case, with credit for 24 days time served; the INITIAL TERM OF CONFINEMENT in the Wisconsin State Prison System is 12 MONTHS; the MAXIMUM TERM OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION is 12 MONTHS.  
AS TO COUNT 5: 
The Court sentenced the defendant to a MAXIMUM TERM INCARCERATION IS 6 MONTHS, concurrent to COUNT 4 and consecutive to any other sentence, with credit for 24 days time served, with no release privileges.
Court costs, fees, assessments and surcharges, including the DNA surcharge to paid through collection by the department of Corrections from 25% of funds under Sec. 973.05(4)(b). Any remaining balance upon release to extended supervision shall be due immediately; failure to pay will result in an entry of civil judgment. 
Defendant IS eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program or the Substance Abuse Program. 
CONDITIONS OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION:
- Maintain Absolute Sobriety, no alcohol.
- No use or possession of controlled substances without a valid 
  prescription taken in the manner and fashion as prescribed.
- Defendant to participate in Alcohol and Drug Assessment
  and successfully complete recommended treatment
  including drug and alcohol testing. 
- Defendant must attend at least one Alcohol and Drug Assessment
  treatment or sobriety support group per week. 
- Mental Health Evaluation and any recommended treatment. Court recommends Trauma Informed         
  Mental Health Treatment. 
- Obtain/Maintain Full Time employment/school or a combination of both. 
- Pay Department of Corrections fees.

Pursuant to Wisconsin Statutes section 973.176, the Court advised the defendant of the following restrictions:  Firearm possession and Voting.
Court advises the Defendant that under Wisconsin Statute 302.113 the amount actually served may be extended, and that the Defendant could serve the entire bifurcated sentence in prison. The Defendant will be subject to certain conditions while on release to extended supervision, and a violation of any of those conditions may result in the Defendant being returned to prison.

The defendant was advised of her constitutional rights and maximum penalties, waived all rights, plead GUILTY and was examined as to the plea. AS TO COUNT 6 and 7-
Pursuant to plea negotiations and on motion of the State, Court ordered COUNT 6 and 7 dismissed and read-in to case for the purposes of sentencing.

Pursuant to Wisconsin Statutes section 973.176, the Court advised the defendant of the following restrictions:  Firearm possession and Voting.
